WEBVTT

00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:02.000
Shiny app walkthrough

00:00:10.480 --> 00:00:16.639
So we had basically two different applications. Again, we had one that was for

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:21.600
them to be able to upload their information that was due at 2 p.m every Wednesday. It was basically

00:00:21.600 --> 00:00:28.959
like hospitals, local health departments, long-term care facilities, higher ed, pre-k through 12. So

00:00:28.959 --> 00:00:34.320
they've created these different customer entities, if you will. They have a template, an Excel

00:00:34.320 --> 00:00:38.880
template. We pulled out a whole bunch of stuff that they used to have to fill out because we

00:00:38.880 --> 00:00:44.320
could automate it for them. So we really pared that down to just get the essential information

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:49.360
that we needed from them and created this interface for them to be able to upload their file.

00:00:49.360 --> 00:00:54.560
Then we save it on the backend and name it. And then we create a whole bunch of new variables

00:00:54.560 --> 00:00:59.680
with the data that they upload. At the time, the only restrictions we really checked for were

00:00:59.680 --> 00:01:04.639
making sure that fields that were required actually had information in them. Some of them

00:01:04.639 --> 00:01:10.080
had to be structured a certain way, things like that. But we didn't necessarily have anything

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:15.919
else that we were checking for. What we built in later on and where the process now starts is when

00:01:15.919 --> 00:01:22.239
the group at the GIATF, which is the Joint Interagency Task Force, that's the group of

00:01:22.239 --> 00:01:27.279
groups, if you will, within our state that's overseeing all of this, when they find out what

00:01:27.279 --> 00:01:33.519
the supply is going to be coming in in the next week from the CDC, they can go into this tab and

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:38.480
they can allocate a certain number. They do it all in vials, but a certain number of vials

00:01:38.480 --> 00:01:45.199
for each entity. So for hospitals, they're only allowed a maximum of 100 Moderna vials. They'll

00:01:45.199 --> 00:01:51.599
put that in here. Pfizer and J&J, they're doing it for all three brands right now of vaccine.

00:01:51.599 --> 00:01:56.559
And so now when they go in to upload their information, we're checking against that.

00:01:56.559 --> 00:02:01.519
If they upload it as a draft, it won't prevent them from uploading, but it will give them a

00:02:01.519 --> 00:02:06.559
message, like a caution message to say, you're over your max allocation, so you need to fix this

00:02:06.559 --> 00:02:11.440
before uploading your final version. And then they can go in and select final and upload their

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:16.559
final version. And then that's really what's used then to create the final distribution report for

00:02:16.559 --> 00:02:23.279
the week. So this is kind of a checks and balances system to make sure that they're not having to go

00:02:23.279 --> 00:02:28.559
back to these people afterward and say, you've asked for too much or to break any hearts later

00:02:28.559 --> 00:02:32.960
on to say, you asked for too much. We're only giving you this amount. Like it's very transparent

00:02:32.960 --> 00:02:37.679
this way. They know how much they're allowed to request for the week. So once that's done again

00:02:37.679 --> 00:02:43.360
by 2 PM on Wednesdays, we go back over here. This is our vaccine demand management application,

00:02:43.360 --> 00:02:48.160
and this is where the bulk of work does happen. They have another tab where they're then able to

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:55.279
go and download the final distribution report. And I should say final loosely. So it's the

00:02:55.279 --> 00:03:02.160
distribution report that's generated based on what was uploaded by the customer entity groups. Then

00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:08.000
we also have an overall vaccine request. You can see over here too, this is a good check for them.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:13.440
They're all working together in a large armory. So technically all of these different people that

00:03:13.440 --> 00:03:17.440
are using the system, at least the two we've talked about so far, on Wednesday afternoons,

00:03:17.440 --> 00:03:22.800
they're all in the same room, but it could be a little walk to go get to them. So this just makes

00:03:22.800 --> 00:03:26.399
it easier. They don't have to get up and go ask the person, hey, have you uploaded your information?

00:03:26.399 --> 00:03:31.440
It's all right here. And they can see which groups have already uploaded, which haven't.

00:03:31.440 --> 00:03:37.520
They can create the reports and download those. So from here, we have a request summary that will

00:03:37.520 --> 00:03:44.479
summarize the total number of vials that need to go to each distribution hub. We have our upload

00:03:44.479 --> 00:03:49.440
status of when the different entities last uploaded. And then this just aggregates all

00:03:49.440 --> 00:03:55.520
of the information that came from the different requesters, the different customers. So it just

00:03:56.320 --> 00:04:03.600
compiles all the different CSV files into one. And then here we have the distribution report. So this

00:04:03.600 --> 00:04:11.119
we're generating a tab for every hub to work from. And then this sixth tab, I'm not going to

00:04:11.119 --> 00:04:17.920
go into that today, but it's similar information about ancillary kit inventory. So not only are

00:04:17.920 --> 00:04:22.480
they tracking the vaccine inventory at the different hub locations, we also have to make

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:28.000
sure that we have syringes and needles and alcohol pads and gloves and all of that fun stuff to go

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:35.040
with the vials of vaccine to be administered. We automated all of this. We have some business

00:04:35.040 --> 00:04:40.320
rules where we're assigning the day of pickup and the time of pickup for the different groups.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:49.920
Again, this is mock data that we use. So everybody is requesting one vial of vaccine, but it has

00:04:49.920 --> 00:04:54.000
county information. It would have a point of contact name and phone number. If they're late

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.160
to their pickup, but didn't communicate anything to the distribution hub, they can easily get a

00:04:58.160 --> 00:05:03.200
hold of the person. From here, there is still a manual process involved and we can't get rid of

00:05:03.200 --> 00:05:10.239
all of them, but our contacts at the National Guard, they'll go in and they will look at what

00:05:10.239 --> 00:05:16.160
was requested. And as long as there are no concerns about supply, as long as demand is

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:20.320
met by the supply, they'll go ahead and confirm that that is in fact what they're going to be

00:05:20.320 --> 00:05:25.119
allotted for that following week. So they can go in here if they need to and make adjustments

00:05:25.119 --> 00:05:31.279
in the allotted vials and allotted doses section if they need to. And we also create a column for

00:05:31.279 --> 00:05:36.320
delivered doses, delivered vials, but really everything, all the inputs we have them do are

00:05:36.320 --> 00:05:40.799
in vials and then we take care of the math on the back end to say how many doses are in each vial

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:47.200
and we take care of that. Once they have all of that finalized for the week, they can, there's a

00:05:47.200 --> 00:05:53.040
separate app where only like two people have access to upload the final version of the distribution

00:05:53.040 --> 00:05:58.640
report. Again, centrally, they can add new work orders if they need to. If a special request comes

00:05:58.640 --> 00:06:03.200
in, they're like, okay, yeah, we have extra supply on hand, we can accommodate that. They have a

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:09.200
tab where they can input that information and it automatically updates the distribution report.

00:06:09.839 --> 00:06:15.200
They can also do change of orders. So if somebody needs additional vials, they can just add it to

00:06:15.200 --> 00:06:19.839
a certain work order instead of creating a whole new one for that same customer. So we gave them

00:06:19.839 --> 00:06:26.880
those features to be able to do that. And while they're making their changes on this end, we also

00:06:26.880 --> 00:06:35.519
allow the hubs, they're able to go into their own application where they're tracking pickups.

00:06:35.519 --> 00:06:40.000
So on this first tab, they'll enter the work order number, they can look it up to make sure they

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:44.320
actually input it correctly, and the total number of vials that were picked up that day.

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:51.679
Then they also can change pickup times or pick up days of the week if they need to. Again, this is

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:58.480
just a way for management to know if something wasn't picked up, why? It's because they changed

00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:03.600
their pickup time, that's fine. And then download distro report. They can download an up-to-date

00:07:03.600 --> 00:07:09.359
version if they want to, but also in this data table view, they can just scroll through or search

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:14.720
for anything in their particular hub. So at any point in time, the hubs are able to download the

00:07:14.720 --> 00:07:20.559
most up-to-date version of the distribution report, as well as management in their vaccine

00:07:20.559 --> 00:07:25.839
demand management application. All of it is as real time as we could make it. And again, we're

00:07:25.839 --> 00:07:31.200
working with people who are used to working in Excel anyway, so we wanted to make sure to keep

00:07:31.200 --> 00:07:39.359
that sort of feature intact for them.

